Raw dev notes -- RAG Pipeline: Battling Big Files and Broken Deploys

Okay, so this project is all about building out a robust RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) knowledge base pipeline. The core idea is to feed our LLM fresh, accurate information from various sources, so it's not just hallucinating or working with stale data. It's essentially the brain that keeps the LLM grounded in reality, constantly updating its understanding of the world.

This past week had some interesting moments. Early on, things seemed pretty smooth. I saw a commit for a routine content sync – `sync: 1 new posts, 0 comment updates`. That's always a good sign, means the pipeline is chugging along, pulling in new articles or whatever content we're tracking and getting it ready for retrieval. It's the bread and butter of keeping the knowledge base fresh.

Then things got a bit spicy. The big one was a fix for `stream-write mega-files + surface deploy failures (#6)`. This was a beast. Turns out, some of the content we're trying to process and write to storage can get *huge*. Like, unexpectedly huge. My initial writing mechanism was just trying to load everything into memory, which, predictably, blew up when it hit one of these "mega-files." It was a classic "works on my machine with small data" scenario that crumbled under real-world scale. The fix involved implementing a proper streaming write, so we're not trying to hold the entire file in RAM at once. That felt like a proper engineering win, making the whole system much more resilient.

The second part of that commit, "surface deploy failures," was directly related to a pretty stressful incident. We had a deployment fail on May 16th, and it was one of those silent, insidious failures. The deployment just... didn't work, and the logs weren't giving me much to go on. It took a fair bit of digging to figure out what was actually going wrong. That led to the `chore: sync .deploy_state.json from 2026-05-16 recovery deploy (#7)` commit. We had to do a "recovery deploy" to get things back online, and then sync up the deployment state file. The lesson there was painful but clear: if a deploy fails, it *needs* to scream about it, loudly and clearly. No more silent failures. I've put in some work to make sure future deployments are much more verbose about their struggles.

Honestly, dealing with that silent deploy failure was frustrating. It felt like I was debugging in the dark for a while, just poking around until something broke in a way I could understand. But getting the streaming write in place and improving the deploy feedback loop felt really good. It's a reminder that anticipating scale and building robust error handling isn't just a nice-to-have, it's absolutely critical. It also reinforced how important good observability is – if you can't see what's happening, you can't fix it. I definitely felt a sense of growth in tackling a real-world production issue and coming out with a more resilient system.

Next up: Looking into more robust monitoring for the pipeline's health.
